In this session, you will read a series of pages about the topics below. Pay attention because you will be asked questions about the information.
* Read the information carefully and really try to understand it.
* Consider all of the information provided, even if some of it seems new to you.

* After you finish a page, the next screen will ask you a question about it.The score in the top right corner shows how many answers were correct on the first try.Click the Continue button once you are ready to begin.

Our goal is to reduce your anxious thinking by changing your understanding of anxiety. In each session, you will learn about anxiety by reading brief information about the topics below and completing questions by answering whether statements are true or false.

As we saw, anxiety is common, useful, and appropriate in situations that threaten someone’s health or well-being. But when someone gets anxious without a true threat or to an excessive degree, the anxiety can be impairing and cause problems in a person’s life. As you learned in Session 1, anxious feelings come with changes in thoughts, bodily reactions, and behaviors. The same types of changes can cause problems with anxiety that mental health professionals call symptoms. Symptoms can vary in how much they affect a person and how long they last.
